Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
create_metric_table(25.10)                          create_metric_table(25.10)

Name
       create_metric_table - Creates a metric table

Syntax
       create_metric_table

       [-help]

       [-auto_hide]

       [-collapsible_key]

       [-format {html excel text}]

       -heading <table_heading>[-hide_footers]

       [-hide_graph_footers]

       [-hierarchy_separator <separator>]

       [-id <table_id>]

       [-key <regexp_key>]

       [-per_snapshot]

       [-show_label_every <frequency>]

        -type  {horizontal  vertical  cpu dict time_statement histogram image-
       plot}

       Creates a metric table.

       To create a metric table, you first need to create a metric page  using
       the  create_metric_page command. After creating a metric page, you need
       to specify the heading for the metric table using the create_metric_ta-
       ble_heading command. After specifying the  metric  table  heading,  you
       create the metric table using the create_metric_table command.

Parameters
       -auto_hide
              Specifies whether to auto hide the table.

              Date_type: bool, optional

       -collapsible_key
              Specifies  to include collapse key columns in the table with the
              option to expand them.

              Date_type: bool, optional

       -format {html excel text}
              Specifies configuration for the report_metric format.

              Date_type: enum, optional

       -heading <h> <eading_id>
              Specifies the id of the heading to append. You need  to  specify
              the  table  heading  already created using the create_metric_ta-
              ble_heading command.

              Date_type: string, required

              For example, the following command gives an error as the  metric
              table  heading statistics has not been defined before specifying
              the heading while creating the table.

              @[DEV]innovus 5> create_metric_table -id table_id -heading  sta-
              tistics -type horizontal

              heading id {statistics} not found

              @[DEV]innovus  6>  create_metric_table -heading statistics -type
              horizontal

              heading id {statistics} not found

              @[DEV]innovus 7>

       -hide_footers
              Hides the minimum, average, and maximum rows from the bottom  of
              the table. Graph buttons are still shown.

              Date_type: bool, optional

       -hide_graph_footers
              Hides the graph buttons from the bottom of the table.

              Date_type: bool, optional

       -hierarchy_separator <separator>
              Shows the metric names with hierarchy using the provided separa-
              tor.

              Date_type: string, optional

       -id <table_id>
              Specifies the id for the new table.

              Date_type: string, optional

       -key  <regexp_key>
              Specifies the key for any regexp.

              Date_type: string, optional

       -per_snapshot
              Specifies to expand the table per snapshot.

              Date_type: bool, optional

       -show_label_every <frequency>
              Specifies the frequency of X-axis labels in the histogram.

              Date_type: int, optional

       -type {horizontal vertical cpu dict histogram imageplot}
              Specifies  the  type (horizontal vertical cpu dict histogram im-
              ageplot) of table.

              Date_type: enum, required

Example
       The following commands create the table_s metric table:

       innovus1> create_metric_page -name User

       innovus2> create_metric_table_heading -id statistics -page User \

         -title "Average Timing Values Per Snapshot"

       innovus3> create_metric_table  -id table_s -heading statistics \

         -per_snapshot -type  horizontal

